        "category": "Service",
        "image": "",
        "description": "A 3D printed lithophane is a 3D object, typically made from translucent plastic, that reveals a photographic image when backlit, with darker areas of the photo represented by thicker, less translucent parts of the print and lighter areas by thinner parts, creating a luminous, embossed picture when light shines through it. Essentially, it converts a 2D image's brightness into 3D depth, forming a detailed photo that's almost invisible until illuminated. \nImage Conversion: Software transforms a digital photo (best with high contrast) into a grayscale height map, where dark pixels become thick material and light pixels become thin.\n3D Printing: A 3D printer builds the model layer by layer, creating varying thicknesses.\nIllumination: When light passes through, thicker sections block more light (appearing dark), while thinner sections let more light through (appearing light), revealing the image. ",
